  "opinion": "As a woman in her sixties who’s been a sales associate in Bologna for decades, I’ve seen how stereotypes can quietly shape people’s confidence in fields like STEM. Stereotype threat isn’t just a theory—it’s something I’ve felt in my own life. Growing up with a parent who had a master’s degree but the other who only finished lower secondary school, I learned early that intelligence wasn’t something you could take for granted. When I first started working in sales, I’d often worry that my lack of technical knowledge might make me seem less capable than my colleagues. That anxiety, I now realize, is stereotype threat: the fear of confirming a negative stereotype about one’s group. In STEM, this can be especially painful for women and people of color, who may internalize the idea that they’re not naturally suited for math or science. But should we address it? Absolutely. In my community, I’ve seen how small changes—like encouraging girls to pursue science through hands-on activities at the local library or supporting women in tech with mentorship programs—can make a real difference. I’ve also noticed that when people feel safe to ask questions without judgment, their performance improves. It’s not about fixing people but about creating environments where everyone feels they belong. I’m an anxious person, so I know that being too critical of myself can hold me back, but I’ve learned that addressing stereotype threat isn’t about blame—it’s about building bridges. In Bologna, where many families value education but face financial constraints, we need to focus on practical solutions that don’t overwhelm those who are already stressed. By making STEM accessible through storytelling and community support, we can help everyone thrive without letting stereotypes hold them back.",
